“ Rumours beyond belief there filled our ears, That Helenus, theson of Priam, reigned O'er those Greek towns, his bride and sceptre won From Pyrrhus, and Andromache once more Had found no alien spouse. My heart amazed Burned to salute him, and to learn his tale. Forth from the port I wend, from ships and shore, When haply in a grove beyond the town, By some feigned Simois stream, Andromache Was shedding her sad gifts, and called his ghost To Hector's tomb, an empty mound of turf, And altars twain she hallowed but for tears.
